hook.real_world_problem:
Building a REST API server in plain Java requires:

```java
// Old way — without Spring Boot:
// 1. Download and configure Tomcat (50MB server, XML config)
// 2. Write web.xml deployment descriptor (100+ lines)
// 3. Configure DispatcherServlet manually
// 4. Set up connection pooling
// 5. Configure Jackson for JSON
// 6. Wire all components together manually
// 7. Deploy WAR file to server
// Total setup: ~2 hours, ~500 lines of boilerplate
```

**With Spring Boot:**
```java
// Application.java:
@SpringBootApplication
public class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args);
    }
}
```

```java
// OrderController.java:
@RestController
public class OrderController {
    @GetMapping("/orders")
    public List<String> getOrders() {
        return List.of("ORD-001", "ORD-002");
    }
}
```

Run `main()`. Your API is running on port 8080. Embedded Tomcat included. JSON serialization configured. Zero XML. Zero WAR. Zero infrastructure setup.

This is Spring Boot's promise: **production-ready features with minimal configuration**. One annotation, one method call, and you have a server. The rest of Module 13 builds the full production REST API.

concept_explanation.spring_boot_application:
**@SpringBootApplication — the magic annotation:**

```java
@SpringBootApplication  // three annotations in one:
// @Configuration: marks this class as a Spring config source
// @EnableAutoConfiguration: enables Spring Boot's auto-configuration
// @ComponentScan: scans this package (and sub-packages) for Spring components
public class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creates the ApplicationContext (Spring's IoC container):
        SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args);
        // → starts embedded Tomcat
        // → loads all @Components
        // → wires all dependencies
        // → ready to handle HTTP requests
    }
}
```

**What happens when you call `SpringApplication.run()`:**
1. Creates Spring's IoC container (ApplicationContext)
2. Runs auto-configuration based on classpath
3. Scans the package for @Component, @Service, @Controller, @Repository
4. Wires all dependencies (dependency injection)
5. Starts embedded Tomcat on port 8080
6. Your app is running

concept_explanation.dependency_injection:
**Dependency Injection (DI) — Spring's core:**

Instead of creating dependencies yourself, Spring creates and wires them:

```java
// WITHOUT DI (manual):
class OrderService {
    private OrderRepository repo = new OrderRepositoryImpl();  // you create it
    private EmailService emailSvc = new EmailServiceImpl();      // you create it
    // Tightly coupled. Hard to test. Hard to swap implementations.
}

// WITH Spring DI:
@Service
class OrderService {
    private final OrderRepository repo;
    private final EmailService emailSvc;

    // Constructor injection — Spring provides these:
    @Autowired
    OrderService(OrderRepository repo, EmailService emailSvc) {
        this.repo = repo;
        this.emailSvc = emailSvc;
    }
    // Loosely coupled. Testable with mocks. Swap implementations easily.
}
```

**Spring stereotype annotations:**
```java
@Component    // generic Spring-managed bean
@Service      // business logic layer (same as @Component, semantic clarity)
@Repository   // data access layer (+ exception translation)
@Controller   // web layer (handles HTTP requests)
@RestController // @Controller + @ResponseBody (returns JSON directly)
```

All four register the class as a Spring bean — Spring creates one instance and manages it.

concept_explanation.spring_bean_lifecycle:
**Spring beans — creation, injection, destruction:**

```java
@Service
public class ProductCatalogService {

    // After bean is created and all @Autowired fields are injected:
    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        System.out.println("Loading product catalog from DB...");
        // Runs once when Spring creates this bean
    }

    // Before the bean is destroyed (app shutdown):
    @PreDestroy
    public void cleanup() {
        System.out.println("Releasing resources...");
    }

    public List<Product> findAll() { return catalog; }
}
```

**Bean scope:**
```java
@Component
@Scope("singleton")   // default: one instance shared everywhere
class CacheService { ... }

@Component
@Scope("prototype")   // new instance on every @Autowired injection
class RequestLogger { ... }
```

Singleton (default) is almost always right. Prototype is for stateful objects that shouldn't be shared.

